When I was outside leaving the facility, I noticed a tight knot in my chest.Less than a half an hour later,I had pulled over in the park and was trying to fix myself. Soon I realized breathing was not helping. It didn't seem to work. Exercise did not help. I started getting worse. I had difficulty getting back to my car I was fatigued my vision was getting blurry.My thinking was not sure. I couldn't figure out how to get my seat down in my car. Finally I got it down enough so I could recline. Then I decided to try to use my I watch pull up my Hart app.I measured over 155 bpm. I noticed that I was feeling better as my heart rate decreased to 141 bpm. I decided to drive home and left my car seat reclined. When I got h I stayed laying down in my bed for two hours because when I tried to get up I was way too dizzy. I've been unable to reach my primary care doctor when I got home.  I left a voice messages. I called my sisters to tell them what was wrong and while on the phone St. Luke's was trying to call me and then my sister said she had to hang up because St. Luke's was trying to call her.  I got up when I heard a knock on the door. It was the police. St. Luke's had called the police.  My heart rate was normal before I got up Almost 3 hours after my shot.  I spent the rest of the day and the next morning trying to find out what happened to me. I have spent days trying to get warnings about what to look out for.  Finally I found this on your website as well as the handout I should've had before the vaccine because I would've known what was happening to me and what to do.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Was napping the day after receiving the vaccine and woke up about 3:00 pm to severe chest pain on the right side radiating deep into the shoulder blade.  It would last about 5 - 10 min., stop for the same amount of time, then start up again.... on & off until close to 11:00 pm.   Since someone else I know had the same thing happen the day after her shot, I assumed I had the same symptom, tho' it was very frightening.  A week later after going to bed on Friday night, I woke at 2:00 a.m. to the same pain only this time on my left side.  Thinking I could be having a heart attack, I went to the hospital where I was admitted after having a series of tests.  I was there for 2 days during which time I also began to have un-controllable diarrhea.  Altho' they could find nothing wrong with my heart,  after scans, x-rays, a stress test, numerous blood tests etc., they cannot say positively whether or not it was from the Covid vaccine.  I tho't it best to report this in case others have similar events.  I had the MODERNA vaccine
LAB_DATA: Nothing to show any heart problems.  Dr. couldn't tell me what was wrong.  I had numerous heart tests, blood work, etc.  Nothing showed that it was heart related.  Dr. couldn't tell me what the pain was caused from.  I believe it was the Moderna shot, especially since someone else I know who is 30 yrs. younger had chest pain also on the day after her shot.  However, we may never know.  I just felt it  necessary to report the incident in case others have the same results.
OTHER_MEDS: Atenalol 50 mg 3 x daily, Levothyroxine 88 mcg 1 x daily, Hydrochlorothiazide 12.5 mg 1 x daily, simvastatin 10mg 1 x daily,  Omeprazole 20 mg 1 x daily,  1 Baby aspirin daily.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA I noticed a small, kidney bean shaped blister appear about 24 hours after my vaccination.  It was off to the side of the actual injection site- but only by about an inch or so.  It didn't hurt, was not red.  It continued to swell throughout the next 12 hours, but did not increase in size.  To prevent it bursting, I did drain it, with a sanitized safety pin.  Liquid was clear.  Blister filled up again within 6 hours.  I left it alone.  Between 4 and 5 days after my vaccination, blister was flat, but turned a deep red/purple color- sort of like dried blood/old blood.  I continued to put first aid ointment and a band aid on it for another 24 hours.  As of yesterday, a week after vaccination, dead skin from blister has peeled off, and new skin seems fine.  I am continuing putting first aid ointment on it daily.  Still no pain on that location.  I did take a photo at the time I first noticed it.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I am twenty-eight years old, young, healthy active girl. I have always been into fitness and yoga. I live a generally healthy lifestyle. I have been a singer, a dancer, and a flight attendant! I decided sign up for the COVID-19 vaccine in order to help our world fight against this pandemic. I wanted to protect my family and friends to eradicate this virus once and for all. It was with no hesitation did I jump at the opportunity to get this vaccine when it became available to me on February 12th, 2021 at the Convention Center. As soon as I received my shot I proudly posted my photo with tears in my eyes letting the world know that we were one human closer to a COVID-19 free world. I was Moderna proud.   My entire family had already received their Moderna vaccines because I come from a family of nurses, but none of them had experienced any side effects. I was confident I would be in the clear after their clear symptom free vaccine. Immediately following my vaccine my arm was a little sore, as expected. However, I did experience fatigue and mild leg cramps in my calves. One very odd symptom was that I could taste the vaccine in my mouth, like a metallic, strange taste, which I reported to my family, but everyone just laughed it off. The leg cramps went away after a day or two as well as the taste, but the fatigue continued throughout the week. I felt these symptoms were pretty average. I signed up for the V-Safe reporting system and put in my report and thought nothing of my initial vaccine symptoms.   Things took a very strange turn on the morning of February 20th, 2021 at about 10am. I woke up and my face was numb, tingling all over, twitching in different parts of my face pretty severely and uncontrollably. By 4pm the tingling moved into both of my arms and hands and by 5pm it moved into both of my legs. Shortly after the cramping and twitching began in both of my legs and I lost the ability to walk, lift my legs, and just the ability to feel my legs at all. I could not walk.  Obviously concerning, I thought I was originally having a reaction to a medication I had been taking for over a year called, Topamax, a nerve pain medication which can cause numbness and tingling as a side effect. I called my prescribing physician and he immediately ruled out the possibility of a reaction to this medication due to the length of time I had been on this medication, that I had not missed a dose, I had not increased or decreased the dose, and I had not experienced a reaction like this in the time that I had been taking the medication. He recommended I keep an eye on my symptoms and go to an emergency room if things worsen.   Overnight, my symptoms remained the same. I woke up on Sunday, February 21st, 2021 and I still could not walk, I could not feel my legs. My legs were still twitching and cramping. My face was still numb and tingling, but the twitching had stopped in the face. My hands had stopped tingling. At this point my mother who is a nurse suggested that I call Moderna, the vaccine provider, to report a possible side effect of the vaccine. Upon contacting Moderna, the company thought that it could possibly be a reaction between the Topamax medication and the vaccine, but they had no current information about these two having any interactions. They thanked me for reporting and told me to go to an emergency room if my symptoms continued or worsen.   Throughout the day on Sunday, February 21st, my symptoms remained. I was able to get to my feet, but I walking like a newborn baby giraffe or as my mother described, like a 105 year old woman. I was unable to feel my legs completely, lift them, move them without lifting them with physical help of my arms moving them. At this point on Sunday night I decided to contact my Primary Care Physician. She noted that this sounded similar to Guillain-Barre and that I sound immediately go to an Emergency Department before the symptoms get any worse. It was late on a Sunday night and I was unable to drive myself, so I waited.   Overnight on Sunday into Monday I began experiencing light flashes in my eyes, heart races, lower back pain, and worsening cramping in my legs. I knew that I needed to seek treatment in an emergency room.   On Monday, February 22nd, 2021 I was taken to the Emergency Room Department. They conducted blood work and a physical examination, but did not want to proceed with any MRI?s or CAT scans. The ER the doctors were baffled. They could not figure out what was causing my paralysis other than the vaccine was the only new thing that had been introduced to my body, but they could not verify or diagnose anything. They let me go with a referral to neurology.   While we were sitting in the ER my cousin, a nurse anesthetist at another local hospital, called my mother who was with me with some very alarming news. Her co-worker, had experienced the same symptoms back in December and was just going through recovery after his first dose of the COVID-19 vaccine. He was told by the CDC there had been 19 reported cases through the CDC where after the first dose of the vaccine people have reported numbness, tingling, and the lose of the ability to walk after receiving the first dose of the mRNA vaccine, both Moderna and Pfizer. Her co-worker was also in the same age range as myself, very healthy, young, active. He was officially diagnosed with Transverse Myletis. He has taken a full two months to regain the ability to walk and still has numb patches on his legs. He walks very slowly, but is walking. He returned to work, but cannot return to his normal life working out and being active because he does not have the strength. He was told not to get the second dose of the vaccine.   There are unreported cases in this area by physicians who do not know where to turn with this information. It is hard to link these symptoms and cases because they are so obscure, but these same symptoms are occurring with those who have also had COVID-19. When I was being seen for an EMG test of my legs the physician performing the test said to us, ?I have a patient who received the vaccine and has the symptoms, maybe I should report it!?. My Grandmother?s physician just last week just sent a patient of hers with the same symptoms to neurology. I think this uncommon side effect is more common than is being reported and no one knows where to turn with the information.   I finally got into the head of Neurology. I was told, ?it?ll probably get better?, basically saying that they don?t know what they can do and they are at a loss for knowing what this is and why this is happening to people after the first dose of the mRNA vaccine. Doctors don?t have answers and the vaccine companies aren?t offering information to help link these side effects together. The physician told me not to proceed with the second dose of the vaccine due to neurological side effect that I have had. I should benefit from the first dose and it is not safe for me to get the second dose from this side effect.   I was unable to walk for weeks since this began on Feb. 20th. It is just now that this week I am slowly able to move my legs, but they are still very numb and heavy. I haven?t been able to drive or live my normal life. I cannot use stairs, walk long distances, stand for very long periods of time. I am twenty-eight years old and I walk like an eighty year old woman, wobbly.   I have reported my case to CDC, V-SAFE, Moderna. The CDC said they would be in contact with me due to my report of extreme adverse side effects via the V-SAFE report, but I have not heard anything from them as of today.  These are the uncommon side effects that need to be heard and reported. I don?t know why they are being ignored because I have been left without answers and without hope.

When I received my 2nd shot on 02-22-2021, I could feel it moving down my arm.  Within a couple of hours, it had settled in the back and inside of my arm, just above my elbow.  The area was about 5 inches long and about 3 inches wide.  About 7:00 that night, I was getting chills, then a fever and a severe, piercing headache along with body aches.  My temp is normally about 97.3 degrees, but for the next 36 hours or so, it ran between 97.6 and 100.4  degrees.  I began taking Tylenol when it reached 100 degrees.   On 03-01-2021, I ran chills again, with my temp getting up to 99 degrees.  I also got that severe, piercing headache again. It lasted nearly 24 hours.   Since that day, I have had that piercing headache a few times, but it hasn't lasted long.   (NOTE:   I have had very few headaches in my lifetime.  The last one was probably about 15 years ago, when I had the flu.)  Also, about 3 or 4 days after receiving that 2nd shot,  I opened a drawer in my dresser and the pain shot down from the tips of my fingers to my wrist.  By that evening, the pain had  continued down to that spot just above my elbow, where the shot had settled.  My fingers,  hand, wrist and arm hurt very badly for the next 3 days.  The pain did not go past that spot on my arm where the shot had settled.  The next day it didn't hurt as badly and the next day, the pain was gone.    Also, my 89 year old mother had her 2nd shot the same day as I did and had no affects at all, not even a sore arm.  My 72 year old husband also got his 2nd shot that day and only the area where he got the shot was sore.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I became progressively more sleepy the afternoon after the vaccination, as expected.  I did get up and make dinner, then went to bed at 9:15 p.m. on March 8th and slept until 9:15 a.m. March 9th.  I felt unstable walking into the bathroom to urinate, and even more unstable waking into the kitchen to take my meds. I passed out and woke up on the floor.  I was weak but managed to pull myself up holding on to the kitchen range. I headed for the living room sofa and passed out again, waking up on the floor by the sofa.  I'm guessing I was unconscious about 2 minutes each time, but don't really know. I lay down on the sofa and called a neighbor.  He thought I should call 911, and they came and drove me to  ER .  They did an EKG, chest x-ray, and CAT scan of my brain, and drew blood.  All results were normal. I returned home that same day (March 9)  and had little energy, and ate lightly.  When I was getting in bed about 10:30 p.m. I let my head drop on the pillow and the room started to whirl around me for about six seconds.  Sometimes when I roll over in bed during the night there is a pause before   it feels like the room gives one spin.  My scalp is very tender in the large area where I hit it twice when passing out.  I'm taking it easy again today, but do feel a little stronger.  I am normally exceptionally healthy for my age, and work , traveling to destinations to research and photograph my articles. Both the travel and article take stamina, and I thrive on the work.
LAB_DATA: EKG Chest Xray Cat scan of brain Bloodwork

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Flu vaccine and Tdap vaccine administered RN and Nursing Student. Within 30 seconds the pt stated that she was feeling dizzy and that her legs were feeling tingly. I helped the pt to elevate her legs and reclined her head slightly. on the exam chair. Pt leaned forward with eyes closed. Pt was slumped over and had some loss of color in the face and lips. I helped the pt to sit up while saying her name. No response from pt. Pt began to make grunting sounds, and her body appeared to be jerking. I was beside the pt to prevent her from falling. The pt appeared to be sweating. Her shirt was wet on the front and back. I heard flatulation sounds. This lasted for approximately 2 minutes. RN called for help. Two other RNs came to the room. Nurse was saying the pt's naame, and another nurse was holding an alcohol pad to the pt's nose. The pt's head was reclined slightly. I left the room to get the crash cart, and I notified, FNP about the situation. I arrived back to the pt's room with the crash cart, and FNP assessed the pt. At this time, the pt was alert and oriented. The other jerking  and grunting had subsided. She was laying on her side holding an emesis bag. Pt stated that she was feeling nauseated. RN got the vials machine and checked the pt's vital signs starting at approximately 0920. The pt's BP was 97/65 ans trending up to 135/63 after 3 checks per RN. She instructed me to check again in 5 minutes. The pt stated that she was feeling better. I checked her VS again. Her BP had dropped to 78/52, and she stated that she was feeling hot, nauseated, and dizzy. I held an ice pack covered with a towel on her forehead. She stated that she did not eat anything today. She was given an orange juice and peanut butter crackers. She drank a few sips of juice, and she ate 2 crackers. The vital signs were checked every 5-10 minutes until approximately 1005. BP was trending up. Pt denied feeling dizzy, sweaty, nauseated, and hot. When asked how she felt, she stated that she felt good at this time. Pt stated that she did not need an ambulance to be called. Pt stood up slowly and walked. She stated that she was still feeling well, and that she did not have any concerns or abnormal symptoms. I encouraged the pt to notify her PCP of this occurrence.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within 5 hours, patient was awakened from her nap but found that her eyes were swollen shut, upper lip was swollen and her gums itched.  Her head was hurting which is what awakened her.  She went and looked in the mirror, she immediately took a Benadryl 25 mg oral gel cap.  Within 20 minutes, the swelling and itching started to improve.  The symptoms resolved after taking the Benadryl.  The next day, she went to work.  She took another Benadryl at 10 AM on Friday, slept all day.  She ran errands on Saturday, took a Benadryl with her just in case.  She also carried an Epi pen.  Her feet began to swell, her hands swelled and she started itching all over.  Her throat began to close.  She took a Benadryl immediately (this is day 3).  The symptoms did resolve.   She returned home.  On day four, she had some nausea.  On day five (Monday), she went to work and her tonsils started throbbing.  She ran her bus driver route.  She was itching all over again.  She took another Benadryl . She called Dr. on day 5 after vaccination because of the recurring symptoms.  She also called her allergist.  She had an appointment with her allergist on day 6.  Family Doctor also called back on Day 5 and called a prescription in for Prednisone.  She did not start the Prednisone.  She did see the allergist on day 6. The allergist thinks her reaction might have been due to the preservative in the Moderna product.  It was the only ingredient in both the flu shot (7 years ago) and the Moderna contents.  She advised her to take the Prednisone dose pack (as prescribed by family doctor) to over-ride and she upped her Zyrtec to bid.

Six hours later, the patient was rushed to the local emergency room (ER) after being found unresponsive with tactile fever, bowel and bladder incontinence. At the ER, the child was afebrile, with heart rate 136 beats per minute, blood pressure 95/57 mm Hg, respiratory rate 22 breaths per minute and oxygen saturation 88% on ambient air. The patient was noted to have recurrent, prolonged generalised tonic clonic seizures, and the patient was treated with multiple doses of intravenous lorazepam and a 20 mg/kg loading dose of levetiracetam. The patient required endotracheal intubation due to respiratory failure in the setting of these seizures and seizure treatments. Her laboratory workup, including electrolytes, liver function tests and complete blood count, was normal. The respiratory viral PCR panel via nasal swab was positive for influenza type B. The patient was transferred to PICU on a mechanical ventilator with propofol infusion for sedation. On arrival to the PICU, the child's vital signs were stable, but her Glasgow coma score was low off sedation, and her pupillary response was sluggish to light bilaterally. Fever and seizures recurred. The patient was treated with additional intravenous lorazepam and an intravenous loading dose of fosphenytoin with subsequent resolution of clinical seizures. The neurology consultation service recommended continuous electroencephalogram (EEG) and maintenance dosing of levetiracetam. EEG was consistent with moderate to severe encephalopathy. There were no seizures during the entirety of her 36-hour recording. Despite discontinuation of sedation on hospital day 1, the child remained unresponsive with weak cough and gag reflexes for the initial 4 days of her admission. The patient had generalised hypotonia and decreased strength in all extremities. Following receipt of steroids and intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG), there was a gradual improvement in her neurological status starting with spontaneous eye opening and an improved cough/gag reflex. At the time of her extubation on hospital day 12, there were already concerns about her vision. Subsequent ophthalmology exam was significant for minimal pupillary response to light and diffuse visual field restriction in total superior temporal, inferior temporal, superior nasal, inferior nasal fields. The patient had no perception of bright light consistent with total blindness. Perimetry and visual evoked potentials were attempted but not completed as child was younger and not cooperative. By the time of discharge on hospital day 16, she was walking, talking and eating food by mouth; however, the patient still had visual impairment and could not track or reach objects. Blood glucose and serum electrolytes were within normal limits throughout her hospitalisation. Liver and renal function tests were within normal limits. C-reactive protein (CRP) was less than 0.5 mg/dL on admission. CRP was as high as 5.3 mg/dL on hospital day 2, which trended down to normal from hospital day 3. Antinuclear antibody screen was negative, complement levels (C3 and C4) were within normal limits. Chest X-ray showed right upper lobe and left lobe atelectasis, with resolution within few days while intubated. Neuromyelitis optica (NMO)/aquaporin-4-IgG in serum and cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) were negative, and myelin oligodendrocyte glycoprotein (MOG) antibody assay in serum was negative. CSF analysis was normal with nucleated cells of 3/cubic mm, mildly elevated protein at 85 mg/dL and normal glucose at 66 mg/dL. The CSF meningitis/encephalitis PCR panel was negative. A CT scan of her brain on admission showed mild hypodensities in the left temporal and parietal lobes. Subsequent MRI of the brain showed bilateral, symmetric diffusion restriction of the amygdala, hippocampus, putamen, thalami, pons and regions of the peripheral cortex. [MRI brain findings in a patient with influenza-associated encephalitis/encephalopathy showing the involvement of bilateral putamen and thalami. It showed diffusion restriction in diffusion weighted image. It showed diffusion restriction in apparent diffusion coefficient image]. Faint enhancement of the posterior optic nerves was observed bilaterally on the post-contrast images. [MRI brain with and without contrast findings in a patient with influenza-associated encephalitis/encephalopathy showing enhancement of the posterior optic nerves bilaterally]. MRI C-spine was normal without any demyelinating changes. She was also found to be heterozygous for RAN binding protein 2 (RANBP2) gene mutation on further diagnostic investigation. The working diagnosis at this point was acute necrotizing encephalopathy (ANE) secondary to influenza B infection. The differential diagnosis included NMO, MOG antibody associated encephalopathy, vasculitis and bacterial meningitis. Appropriate workup for these alternative diagnoses was negative. The patient was treated for influenza B infection with oseltamivir for 5 days. The patient was also empirically treated with ceftriaxone and vancomycin until blood, urine and CSF cultures returned negative. Given the working diagnosis of ANE, the patient was given pulse dose steroid therapy with methylprednisolone 30 mg/kg/day from hospital days 3-7 followed by a steroid taper over 3 weeks. The patient was also treated with 0.5 g/kg/day IVIG from hospital days 7-10. The patient continued to improve after the hospital discharge, and within a month, The patient had subjectively regained full vision. At her follow-up visit with neurology, The patient was able to identify colours, and The patient could track objects. Visual acuity testing in neurology clinic was limited as the patient did not cooperate with age appropriate visual acuity testing using the tumbling E vision chart. The patient's parents expressed concerns at that appointment for her learning, stating that it seemed difficult for her to retain new information. Neuropsychology evaluation was scheduled. Patient was scheduled to have an ophthalmology appointment the following week but was then lost to follow-up. The child and her family members were referred to genetics clinic, pending additional genetic testing at the time of this case report. This case has been considered as serious due to hospitalization.  The author commented, "Influenza-associated neurological manifestations vary from encephalitis/encephalopathy, myelitis, Guillain-Barre syndrome and Reye's syndrome, to ANE. Influenza type A is the predominant cause of IAE in children. IAE is more frequently reported in country than the rest of the world. The incidence of influenza-related neurological complications was 4 cases per 100 000 child-years in the country. Abrupt onset of seizures and loss of consciousness following a short duration of fever are the most common manifestations of IAE. CSF analysis may reveal pleocytosis and/or increased protein; however, normal CSF analysis and negative RT-PCR do not rule out IAE. CT and/or MRI may show diffuse cerebral oedema. Neuroimaging in ANE further shows symmetric necrosis of thalami, cortex, internal capsule and brain stem structures. MRI findings in our index patient were consistent with ANE. Cytokine-mediated vascular inflammation and parenchymal cell apoptosis are the most proposed pathophysiological mechanisms for IAE. While our patient's neurological improvement correlated with receipt of these treatments, it is difficult to interpret whether the treatments caused the improvement or if her improvement was due to the natural course of the illness. Larger studies are needed to determine the efficacy of steroids and IVIG in IAE. Our index case was also found to be heterozygous for RANBP2 gene mutation. This genetic mutation was well studied and was found to be associated with recurrent and familial cases of ANE. Visual defects such as uveitis, optic neuritis, neuroretinitis, retinal infarction and lateral geniculate body (visual pathway relay centre in thalamus) infarction have been reported in paediatric patients with influenza. Blindness in our patient is likely explained by the combination of optic nerve enhancement and ANE affecting the lateral geniculate bodies. Presence of isolated optic nerve enhancement without optic disc oedema in our index case was not reported in previous studies. It was described a child diagnosed with IAE due to influenza B virus infection who developed temporary visual impairment as a sequela." This article corresponding to this case is not available for regulatory submission due to copyright restriction.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: EXTREME body aches and headache.  Joint pain. Dizziness.  Nausea. Weakness.  Fever.  All lasted about 8 hours.  Woke up the next morning feeling completely normal.

Neurological, including trigeminal neuralgia and one Bell's Palsy symptoms.  Tried to complete online at library on 2/24/2021 but timed out at 20 minutes.  Item #18:  CDC asked to report any Bell's Palsy symptoms (also trigeminal neuralgia is related to BP).  48 hrs post vax, mid-afternoon Sat, Feb 6th: Suddenly unable to comprehend book I was reading;  and  there was a physical sensation of irritation just inside my skull, wrapping around my brain (meninges?) -  it did not intrude into brain.  Felt lack of 'presence' in room.  Slightly unstable on my feet.  Believed these were related to vaccine, would soon abate, but, also, that this would be no way to go through life!   These lasted 2-3 hours.  (I neither drink alcohol or take recreational drugs.)  About that time, a 'twinging' precursor to trigeminal neuralgia began �  uncertain whether it was TN?  Recurred every 3 hrs.  But then awakened at 6:30 a.m. by two painful TN jabs, repeated more strongly at 9:40 a,m.  At about 12:30 pm, return of light 'twinging' sensation, then nothing � no recurrence.  3rd TN episode in 3 years, the briefest, the only one not requiring oxcarbazepine.  Checked for Bell's Palsy symptoms (which I've never had):  The left side of my mouth wasn't producing any saliva at all � none.  This improved very slowly, continuing for 5 or 6 days; by far the longest lasting symptom.  About Monday, the 8th, experienced an expanded  time warp driving to library � took forever to reach two roundabouts.  Lucid, alert, vision & reactions normal.  Speed was a mile or two above limit.  No euphoria or nystagmus.  At library, conversation and work seemed normal.  Around the same time I had about an 18 hour complete memory loss with regard to medications.  Two dose periods in succession.    On Monday, Feb 8th, I called our 4 day a week neurologist.  He said the symptoms    were an immune response to the vaccine but that he's never seen them together before.  It was scary.  I'm not going to take the second dose at this time.  And will depend upon PCP.       Filling out this form because you've asked about any adverse reaction related to Bell's Palsy (which TN is closely related to).  I wonder how many others have experienced trigeminal neuralgia symptoms following vaccination?  It's a cumulative disease and devastating in advanced forms.  :-(
OTHER_MEDS: Meds and Supps:        Primidone -  HCTZ � Warfarin � Amlodipine -  Alprazolam � Acyclovir - Acetaminophen - Latanaprost -  Multi-vitamin - Vit C � Magnesium � Glucosomine - Vit D3 - AREDS Eye complex

SYMPTOM_TEXT: One week after vaccination, patient awoke with intense generalized itching  (she described as a "internal burning itchiness" that was "all over").  She saw no rash or hives. She looked more carefully and found a few small similar patches on both arms and legs.  Treated with OTC lotion, CeraVe Itch Relief Lotion from store.  Patient says 12 hours after onset that the "insane burning/ itching has subsided for now."  Patient reports no new foods, clothing, washing machine detergent, illnesses, or other exposures.  I am a physician, and the patient called me (her brother) to ask me whether this was a known side effect of the Janssen COVID vaccine.  I did not see this described in the FDA advisory committee data package, but just a general reference that urticaria would be an expected side effect to a vaccine.

69 year old male with a PMH of hypertension and T2DM who was admitted on 3/12/2021 for lactic acidosis, hyperglycemia (to 580s), RUE weakness/dysarthria/weakness (now resolved), and septic shock of unknown etiology.   Outside Hospital: Seen at ED where a stroke code was called for headache, RUE weakness, dysarthria with a CT and CTA that were negative for any acute changes. He he was febrile to 102.2, tachycardic to 130s, hypotensive with pressures in the 80s systolic unresponsive to fluids, leukocytosis to 15 and lactate of 3.5. He was started on vancomycin, ceftriaxone, ampicillin, acyclovir, and dexamethasone. Additional workup including an LP, UA, and CXR were all unremarkable. He was transferred here due to a lack of beds. Of note, the patient received his second COVID-19 vaccine dose on 3/10 and had been febrile since the morning of 3/11.   Hospital ICU: Patient is hemodynamically stable and has been fully weaned off pressor support. His hyperglycemia is decreasing satisfactorily to insulin and is receiving IVF. Repeat lactate for PM of 3/12 and workup for TIA initiated.      Assessment and plan :   69 year old male with a PMH of hypertension and T2DM who was admitted on 3/12/2021 for lactic acidosis, hyperglycemia (to 580s), RUE weakness/dysarthria/weakness (now resolved), and septic shock of unknown etiology requiring vasopressors, antibiotics, and TIA workup. I have personally reviewed the daily labs, imaging studies, cultures and discussed the case with referring physician and consulting physicians.  My assessment and plan by system for this patient is as follows:   Neurology/Psychiatry:  # RUE Weakness, headache, dysarthria Presented to Hospital with RUE, headache, and dysarthria with negative CT and CTA. The patient has a known hx of diabetes and hypertension with a recent elevated A1c. His hypotension as a result of sepsis may have revealed territories in his cerebrum particularly affected by his likely vascular disease. Will initiate TIA workup. Pending results, will consider Neurology Consult. Plan: - ASA 81 mg PO daily - Echocardiogram - Fasting lipid panel - Bilateral carotid artery ultrasound   Cardiovascular: # Hemodynamics, Rhythm, Ischemia # Septic Shock Weaned off NE, still on Vasopressin 2.4. Monitor shows NSR in the 70s. Has now been weaned off vasopressors. Plan: - Weaned off pressors   # History of hypertension Plan: - HOLD PTA lisinopril   Pulmonary/Ventilator Management:  # Airway, Oxygenation, Ventilation, Mechanics: No airway in place. Unlabored breathing on room air without assistance with sats in mid-90s. Plan: - Monitor   GI and Nutrition :  # BMs/Gas/Feedings: Reports having diarrhea. No enteral feeds. Plan - Monitor electrolytes   Renal/Fluids/Electrolytes:  # Electrolytes, Acid/Base, Volume Patient is septic and requiring pressors. He is also having diarrhea, so monitor electrolytes, creatinine, UOP. Glucose responding to insulin, most recently 159. If this afternoon's lactate and creatinine normalize this afternoon 3/12/21 and the patient continues to eat/drink ok (which he has been), then we can turn off his IVF. Plan: - HOLD Metformin given elevated creatinine and risk of metabolic acidosis - Lactated Ringers at 75 mL/hr continuous - Trend BMP - Monitor UOP - Venous Blood Gas - Electrolyte replacement per ICU protocols - Generally avoid nephrotoxic agents such as NSAID, IV contrast unless specifically required - Adjust medications as needed for renal clearance - Follow I/O's as appropriate   Infectious Disease:  # Septic Shock # Leukocytosis # Lactic Acidosis # Recent Covid-19 Vaccine Patient was tachycardic to the 130s, hypotensive with systolic pressures in the 80s, and febrile to 102.2 F. Worked up extensively at outside hospital with the following perfomed: Negative CT/CTA, unremarkable lumbar puncture, unremarkable CXR, and unremarkable UA. His pressures were not fluid responsive at that time, so we will continue some further workup here as below. In addition, there remains the possibility that this patient's current status may be a result of the Covid-19 vaccine and cannot be ruled out given its temporal relationship to his presentation. He was sitting on the floor. I told the student to call 911. I continued talking with the pt. as I was preparing the epinephrine and placing a blood pressure cuff on his arm. They performed the second blood pressure reading and the pt. was transferred to their care at that point.

Anaphylaxis - Throat swelled almost completely closed, wheezing, lightheadedness (nearly passed out), throat/neck and injection site were very itchy and swollen, face/eyes swelled up, turned very pale all over, heart palpitations, etc. The next day - severe, horribly painful burning sensation all throughout my body.  Even clothing lightly touching my skin felt like hot razors cutting in to me. Residual swelling of the face/ arm. Migraine. For two weeks after - Very large, hard lump under my skin at the injection site. It was about the size of my hand and was very painful. After a few weeks it went away.  Treatment- large amounts of benadryl. The pharmacist wanted to use an epipen and send me to the hospital, but I refused because I could still get some air in (doctor later told me that my reaction was so severe I should have gone to the hospital). I had to keep taking large amounts of benadryl for the next few days to keep the reaction down a bit.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 3/7/21 ER to inpatient Admission   (covid positive 3/7/21) 3/11/21 Transferred to higher level of care  Date of Service: 3/8/2021            Chief complaint:  Chest congestion   HPI:  Patient is a 78 y.o. male with PMH significant for hypertension, obesity, coronary artery disease and CKD admitted to acute care from ED peR Dr with pneumonia due to COVID-19.  Patient presented to ER brought in by EMS from local residence.  Was complaining of chest congestion.  Patient had been seen in ER earlier same morning complaining of cough.  Was afebrile at that time.  Oximetry 95%.  Rapid COVID positive.  Patient given Decadron 6 mg IV, albuterol inhaler, zinc and BAM(bamlarnivimab 700 mg) IV x1.  Patient discharged home.  Return later that evening per EMS with shortness of breath.  Complaining that congestion was getting worse.  Was now febrile & had fallen trying to get out of recliner.  Vitals upon arrival-temp 102.8� pulse 87 respirations 24 blood pressure 169/71 oximetry 99% on 2 L. patient given Rocephin 1 g IV piggyback, azithromycin 500 mg IV piggyback, normal saline bolus 1 L & acetaminophen  1000 mg IV in ER.  Labs revealed mild leukocytosis white blood cell count 12.5.  Glucose elevated to a 9 but patient had received Decadron previously.  BUN 32 creatinine 1.8.  D-dimer 1240.  No CT chest obtained due to patient's renal status.  Patient subsequently admitted to acute care for further evaluation and treatment to include IV antibiotics supplemental oxygen pulmonary hygiene.  Patient has received 1st COVID vaccine and due to have 2nd vaccine on March 20.   Upon admission patient was continued on Rocephin and azithromycin IV piggyback & Decadron 6 mg IVPB.  Continued hydration fluids normal saline at 100 cc/hour.  Started on IV Remdesivir with loading dose.  DuoNeb nebulizers q.6 hours.  Patient continued on home regimen less Plavix.  Was started on Lovenox 40 mg subcu daily for DVT prevention.  Patient maintaining oxygenation on 2-3 L.  Had initially been on 2.  Was increased to 3 this morning due to decrease in oximetry down to 92%.  Patient continues with exertional dyspnea.  Does have loose nonproductive cough.  Is complaining of pain to the left lower chest wall with cough.  Describes as sharp.  Denies any actual chest pain.  No nausea vomiting.  Last BM yesterday described as normal.  Blood cultures pending no growth at present.  Is currently resting in bed. Is in negative air pressure room.  COVID precautions observed. CASE DISCUSSED WITH DR

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After getting the vaccine in my left arm, I walked to observation area and sat down in chair. Within a minute or so, I noticed my heart rate was slightly elevated and had a strange feeling of unease. Roughly 3-5 minutes later symptoms appeared and I noticed my palms were sweating and I had slightly blurred vision. At this point, I called for a paramedic and told them I wasn?t feeling well. They arrived nearly 15 seconds later (paramedics were stationed all throughout observation area). Symptom severity dramatically increased (very blurred vision, feeling of something clearly being wrong) and was added by a ringing sound in both ears. I was helped into a wheel chair and rolled into an enclosed area with a curtain around for privacy. Gatorade was offered to me and I took a few sips and felt very mildly better. Paramedics reported that my blood pressure was extremely low (63/28). They asked if I wanted to go to the hospital. Symptoms were the same and starting to very slightly get better from the Gatorade so I said let?s wait a few minutes to see how I feel. At this point they took my blood sugar measurement and found that it was also very low (53mg). They gave me some intravenous fluids and a glucose substance that was in a tube (sort of like toothpaste) and within another five minutes I felt considerably better. I received the IV treatment for roughly 20 minutes and symptoms progressively got better over the course of the treatment. My blood pressure went back up to 117/80 and my blood sugar went up to a more normal level as well (I believe they said somewhere in the 90s or low 100?s). After they removed the IV and blood pressure monitor, I rested for roughly 20 minutes before walking to my car and driving home.
LAB_DATA: Blood pressure was very low when first monitored by paramedics roughly 10 min after vaccine: 63/28 Blood sugar very low when monitored roughly 13 min after vaccine was administered. 53mg

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Friday, March 12th, 2021 approximately 10:35 am, 60-year-old female received her first dose of Moderna Vaccine (Lot Number: 003A21A) in her left deltoid at the facility.  Patient received the Moderna Vaccine. After which she sat in the designated medical observation area for her allotted 15 minutes. Approximately nine minutes post-injection around 10:44 am, she felt a bit ?wobbly? when standing up. A medical assistant called Emergency Medical Services (EMS) immediately and the Physicians Assistant went over to assess patient's symptoms.   During the wait time for EMS?s arrival, the physicians assistant performed an assessment. Patient states to have experienced lightheaded-ness, mouth/tongue tingling, shortness of breath and palpitations. She denied throat constriction, denied itching, redness or pain at the site of injection. She said the tingling she did experience resolved around 20 mins post-injection.   During the assessment, the physicians assistant noted clear breath sounds, irregular health rhythm, increased heart rate, extra-ocular movements intact with no nystagmus, no redness or swelling on the injection site and good grip strength.   Upon EMS arrival at approximately 10:48 pm, the firefighters triaged as per their assessment. She expressed that she is taking ?Lexapro? and allergic to sulfa-drugs. She claims to be ?borderline diabetic? and that the lightheaded-ness has ?never happened before?  The EMS took her to a separate room in the building and assessed her further. After approximately 20 minutes she left and did not leave in an ambulance against medical advice.  She left with her husband and went home. She was made aware that she should go to the hospital immediately if she felt her health was compromised.

I went to my doctor this morning who ruled out an ear infection or wax build up. She encouraged me to contact her if it continued after a week. I have only had vertigo two times in my life, both after a physical trauma to my head (car accident when I as 30, and surprise tackle during touch football) when I was 53. This struck me as an unusual side effect  from the vaccine since I have never had vertigo without a prior event like an accident.  I am in good health otherwise.
LAB_DATA: Only a check up with my family physician.

Monitored BP, oxygen, did EKG (normal), symptoms started easing ~ 09:40.  Sent home. Attending PA though it might just be a Vaso-Vagel response, but, after hundreds upon hundred of needles, I've never had such a response, and, my symptoms did not involve a low BP, fainting or nausea, rather I remained conscious, had throat constriction with increased BP and a narrowed pulse pressure  range.

I received my vaccine at 4:09 pm on Thursday, March 11th, 2021. At 4:45 pm I began to get visual abnormalities while driving home in the right quarter of my visual field. It started with perceived motion on the right quarter of my vision that I would compare to the visual effects that occur after staring at an optical illusion , and proceeded to reduced peripheral vision in that side that lasted for about 20 minutes. at 5:00 pm I noticed I was having difficulty reading and typing text messages in my phone, as it felt like I had extreme dyslexia and very low reading comprehension. At 5:35 pm I called my sister, a pharmacy student in Boston, to try to explain my symptoms, but found myself having extreme word aphasia. I could not describe what was happening to me and couldn't recall family members' names, descriptive words, or the name of my dog. I tried to stay calm while she looked things up and began cooking and listening to a podcast, since my comprehension of spoken words was fine. My headache got worse and I took an ibuprofen by 6:00pm. My boyfriend called me at 6:36 pm to check on me, and I found myself talking fluidly to him on the phone. I called my sister to reassure her and the visual abnormalities and reading and speaking issues were all resolved. I took my temperature at 6:36, and it read 99.9 degrees fahrenheit.
OTHER_MEDS: 125 mg of Armodafinil, 10 mg escitalopram, 3mg-0.02 mg nikki 1 tablet of Kroger One Daily Multivitamin supplement for women's health

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pfizer COVID-19 Vaccine EUA  3/2: Pt received Pfizer vaccine 2/26/2021 and started feeling progressively worse - endorsed fever, diarrhea, body aches, trouble breathing, lack of appetite. On 3/2/2021 pt and husband presented to ED. Pt's husband stated that pt had become more and more confused since she received the vaccine and that on 3/2 she could not complete her sentences. Temp 101.6 on arrival, tachycardic in 130s, tachypneic in 120s, but not hypoxic. Patient was given acetaminophen on arrival. IV was inserted and patient was given 1 L intravenous fluid replacement as well as 2 g ceftriaxone for broad-spectrum coverage within 3 hours of arrival. Blood work was drawn that shows no leukocytosis but lactic acidosis to 3.3.  There are multiple electrolyte abnormalities, hyponatremia 127, hypokalemia 2.8, creatinine 1.01, ALT 59 AST 53, ALP 136, total bili 1.3, lactic acidosis 3.3, troponin 0.02. Patient was given 40 mEq of oral potassium.  Additional L of normal saline was given for total of 2 L normal saline bolus.  Chest x-ray shows right basilar pneumonia. Also shows pulmonary nodule of which husband was made aware. LFTs are noted be elevated, so biliary ultrasound was obtained that was negative with limit to body habitus. Husband was updated. Azithromycin was added on. Rapid COVID antigen was negative.  3/3/21: Febrile, SOB overnight. Pt more lethargic, trailing off in the middle of sentences and having difficulties following conversation. Continue sepsis protocol, add vancomycin IV to ceftriaxone and azithromycin. Frequent neuro checks. MRCP. Chest pain-free, serial cardiac enzymes from yesterday to demonstrate nonischemic pattern likely type 2 NSTEMI. 2/2 blood cultures from 3/2 positive for Streptococcus pyogenes (Group A). Vancomycin and azithromycin dc'd.  3/11: Discharged from hospital. Patient admitted for acute hypoxic respiratory failure secondary to right basilar community-acquired pneumonia.  Blood culture grew Streptococcus pyogenes, patient was initially treated with ceftriaxone and switched to Ancef . repeat blood culture on 03/04/2021 showed no growth. Patient will complete a total 14 day course of antibiotics with amoxicillin from culture negative date. Patient had right-sided pleural effusion, pulmonary consulted and she underwent thoracentesis x2 culture showed no growth, considered parapneumonic effusion.  Patient required 2 L continuous oxygen and deemed stable for discharge.  She will follow up with Pulmonary in 3 weeks, outpatient chest CT in 4-6 weeks to be ordered by Pulmonary to assess lung nodule and known thoracic aortic aneurysm.   PTOT recommended home discharge with VNA. On discharge patient was a febrile and hemodynamically stable. Remained COVID negative throughout.
LAB_DATA: Please see description of adverse event.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 79 year old male here for evaluation of possible allergic reaction to Moderna COVID-19 vaccine. 1.Allergic reaction, Urticaria  Pt received hist first dose of the Moderna vaccine on Tuesday, March 9th at 11am in his left arm. On Wednesday he began experiencing chills, felt cold and developed a fever of 101.9. Today his symptoms from yesterday resolved however he developed a pruritic urticarial rash on his upper thighs bilaterally, upper arms bilaterally, lower back and abdomen. He took one tablet of Benadryl this morning which did not improve his symptoms. He is not experiencing any shortness of breath, cough, sore throat, difficulty swallowing or wheezing. He has not tried applying any topical creams or ointments. No new medications, laundry detergents, body wash, perfumes or bedding. No history of allergies to food, environment or medications. He has a history of COVID-19 and was hospitalized 2nd to COVID-19 pneumonia for 25 days in 12/2020.  - Take OTC Claritin during the day and OTC Benadryl at night for one week  - Take 20 mg Pepcid once daily  - Start medrol pack  - Increase fluid intake  - Apply moderate strength triamcinolone ointment to rash  - Labs drawn today will call with results  - Will report allergic reaction to public health department - VAERS - Reviewed previous labs, HGB low  - ER/red flag precautions given.   Followed up with patient today 3/12/2020 over the phone: Called pt to follow up. He reports the rash worsening this morning and spreading behind his knees, behind his thighs and behind his calves mostly on his left leg. He applied the steroid cream this morning and he reports the rash greatly improved afterward reducing to about 10-15% remaining. States his rash is almost gone. Patient has been taking all of his medications as prescribed: Medrol dose pack, steroid cream, Claritin, Benadryl, Pepcid. Advised pt to continue to finish full course of medications as prescribed. PT denies any wheezing, cough, SOB. Advised pt that if symptoms worsen or do not improve over the weekend to go to urgent care or ER if life threatening. Red flag signs and symptoms provided. Pt verbalized understanding.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 31 year old female with a benign medical history who presented for her 2nd SARS CoViD-19 vaccine (Phizer BioNTech) at approximately 1330. At 1345 her vital signs were as follows:   Pulse 109 Respirations 18 SpO2 97% on room air Temp 97.8F BP 140/80 pain 2/10, headache  She reported no prior reaction to her previous vaccine dose. She also endorsed not having anything to eat prior to this vaccine. After resting for 5-7 minutes she developed nausea and vomiting and decided she would like to be evaluated at the ED, but not taken over by ambulance. She was taken by wheelchair accompanied by this provider, a Certified Medical Assistant, and Security to the ED and assisted to check in, and then report was called to the ED Provider on. No medication was administered during this interaction. Patient's headache and nausea persisted though her vomiting subsided. She remained alert and verbally interactive throughout the transport. She was transported at 1355 and report was called at 1424.

Around 5:55 I felt a numbing at the top of my leg while seated while waiting my 15 minute wait time.  The numbing continued down the right side of my right leg. I didn't think much of it because I thought it was the way I was sitting.  I didn't report it to anybody at that time.  I got in my car and my three right toes started to numb.  Then I felt it down my arm and the right three fingers.  About 15 minutes later my jaw muscle, then up to my temple and across the fatty area of the eyebrow went numb.  Several minutes later  I noticed my nostril and right side of my tongue numb.  It felt like my tongue and face were swollen but  when looking in the mirror they were not and there was no drooping when I smiled and raised my eyebrows.  It was a similar feeling that I have had when a shot has almost worn off from a dental procedure.  The feeling and the movement is there but still tingly.   The arm, leg, and toe numbness went away 2-3 hours later on the same day of the shot.  I had no numbness on the left side.    Two days later I still have the same numbness on my right two fingers, tongue, jaw, eyebrow area, and nostril.
LAB_DATA: I called my doctor 3/12/2021 and he said to let him know if I do not improve in a week.  He advised against taking the second dose.

Saturday, 02/20/2021, 1 week after receiving the vaccination, I noticed my left shoulder was itching. When I looked at it, there was sort of a blotchy crescent moon of pink color to the skin, not AT the injection site, but toward the front of the shoulder. The injection was toward the back of the shoulder, as I recall. There were no bug-bite-swollen-raised bumps.  There was intense itching the next morning, 2/21, and the pink color was more of a 1 3/4" circle. Itching subsided but came back that afternoon. I applied a bit of hydrocortisone to the area and the itching subsided.  The next morning, Monday, the area was more filled in with pink and there was a new peninsula of pink descending about 2" below the circle. It throbbed and itched when I first got up. Again there was another surge of itching in the late afternoon. I applied hydrocortisone twice. Tuesday there was no change in the rash or itching in the morning, but no second surge of itching in the afternoon. I messaged my Primary Physician's office and heard back that this could be a reaction to the vaccine, and that I should apply cold compresses to the area. I did. On Wednesday, the bottom of the rash was redder, but the top was fading.By Monday, March 1, no pink was visible.
HISTORY: Hypothyroid (multi nodular goiter), treated Lichen sclerosus Osteoarthritis

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The day after the shot I was tired, groggy and achy. I took two naps and some ibuprofen. In the days following, I experienced severe aches and pains in my upper arms and thighs. This continued and got steadily worse for  two weeks. No fever or loss of taste. I called the doctor and was told people have different reactions, maybe I should get tested for  covid. I did not. Pain continued. I had trouble sleeping, despite constant ibuprofen. I could not turn over in bed. End of the third week I went to an accupuncturist/massage therapist, who has helped me before . I 've had two treatments and am feeling incrementally better each day. Thinking back on how I feel today--which is still achy, as you might feel with the flu--I realize I was in serious agony for those weeks before treatment. Just prior to the shot, I had been for a full physical and bloodwork and was judged by my doctor to be one of the healthiest people in her practice. I was perfectly fine before this shot.

My body was very tired at this point. I slept on & off all day. My temperature went back and forth from about 101-102 the day after the vaccine. I went to sleep that night with a fever, although a little lower. I was taking Tylenol every 6 hours, it was helping but wasn?t making my fever go away. Day two I was weak and had a low grade temperature 99.5-100.5.  Day three I was finally starting to feel like I was getting a bit better. On and off my temperature was going up to 99.5-99.9, but no Tylenol anymore. It was the worst reaction I?ve ever had to a vaccine. I?m still not 100% myself, I still have a nasty headache. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received vaccine at 3:15 pm on 3/12/21 and stayed in pharmacy area for 15 min (he left feeling fine). After about an hour 4:15 he showed back up at the pharmacy telling our pharmacy technician that he lost his voice and his throat was closing. She rushed him to the waiting room where I, pharmacist, came out and asked him what was going on. He stated he was with a client and suddenly lost his voice, and felt his throat starting to close. I asked if he was having trouble breathing and he said yes because his throat was closing and his whole arm was tingling. I had him take his mask down and try to take a few deep breaths first. I asked for permission to administer an Epi-pen which he gave verbal consent. 911 was called. Patient stated he did not want 911 called because he was going to refuse service.  After a min or so patient stated his throat was back open and he was feeling good. I informed him paramedics are on their way and he needed to stay in the waiting room because effects of the EpiPen can wear off in 15 min.  I stayed with him and watched until paramedics arrived. Paramedics sat with him and he did refuse service (they did take his blood pressure).  When paramedics asked the patient about when he came in they asked if he was having trouble breathing and he responded "no I could breathe, my voice was just hoarse" (which is the opposite of what he told the technician and myself). He also sounded like it was very hard to breathe. I did information to the paramedics after saying that he told us his throat was closing of which they stated that they figured that was the case and they knew the patient and assumed he would refuse service.   Patient was in contact with his primary care doctor who told him he could go home if his BP was ok but to make sure he had someone to drive him home.  Patient had his wife come to get him and they left.

3 days ; This letter is to inform you of the unfortunate series of events that landed me in hospital on Friday, January 8, 2021. You denied a brain MRI on January 4th that was an emergent situation, mainly because you had no information about what was happening. I am going to lay out the entire timeline of events, as there are more bills coming.  First, I want to give you some background: I am an EXTREMELY fit 64 year old. I work out 6 days a week doing workouts that most 25 year old could not do. I see my OB/GY once a year for my annual checkup. My blood pressure has never been above 110-115/60-70. For my entire adult life, I have never had any serious illness. I should be a dream case for any insurer.  I am married to a Board-certified physician in spinal cord injury medicine, EMG, and Neuromuscular Medicine. Together we run the top EMG lab. We have close relationships with the top specialists, which allowed me access to them very quickly.  Here is the timeline:  On Sunday, December 27, 2020, I was cleaning the baseboards in the bedroom walking backwards. I turned around and hit my left temple HARD on the TV mounted on the wall. I did not pass out, but I actually felt my brain hit the right side of my head from the force. I called my husband and we decided to keep a close watch on me to be sure I did not have a subdural hematoma. For the entire following week, I just had a terrible headache and neck pain. He thought I had a whiplash sort of injury.  On Saturday, 1/2/21, I received my first Moderna Covid vaccine.  On Monday, 1/4/21, I drove to work. I noticed my vision was a little blurry cut chalked it up to needing new contact lenses. When I got in the car and started driving home, I realized that I had complete and total double vision. I only got home by covering one eye to see the road. I was petrified.  On Tuesday morning, my husband called Dr, concussion specialist. He told me to schedule a brain MRI asap. I scheduled it for Friday, 1/8 so company could get approval from you. When we told Dr it was scheduled for Friday, he said I needed it sooner than that, and that he would call in the kind of images he wanted. My friend, who runs the company, got me in that day, and I had an appointment with Dr the following morning, Wednesday, 1/6.   I had a very thorough exam with Dr, who said I had a concussion with a partial 6th nerve palsy (double vision). He DID say it was unusual to develop 6th nerve palsy a week after I hit my head, but we were still thinking it was from the concussion.  On Friday, 1/8, I was driving to the office with my husband (still could not drive). I ate a breakfast sandwich in the car, and when I went to look in the mirror to see if I had food in my teeth, I noticed I could not move the right side of my mouth. By the time we got to the office, I had a palsy on the entire right side of my face. We called Dr who advised that I go to the ER immediately, as 7th nerve palsy is really not associated with a concussion.  We cancelled our patients and he drove me the ER. There I saw Dr, the ER doc, who took one look at me and said I had Bell's palsy. They started taking my vitals and my blood pressure was 220/110! They thought I was having a stroke! They immediately started an IV with medication to reduce my blood pressure. The neurologist came in and ordered another brain MRI with smaller slices than the 1st one to make sure we were not missing anything. He also ordered an MRA. They were all normal. They admitted me to the hospital. After consultation with the Internal Medicine doc, they decided I needed a spina; tap to rule of the many very serious things associated with Bell's palsy. Everything was negative. I was discharged at 1 pm on Sunday, 1/7.  I had a follow up with Dr on Wednesday, 1/13.  We received a call from Dr who insisted on taking over my case, as he knows my husband very well. I had a consultation with him on Wednesday, 1/13. I gave him the entire timeline of events. I was stunned to hear his opinion: BOTH the 6th nerve palsy AND the 7th nerve palsy were caused by my Covid vaccine. He said he had seen 4 patients in the last 10 days who all developed palsies after their vaccines. They were all Pfizer vaccines, and I was the first Moderna one he had seen.   I have since come under the care of Dr who is monitoring my blood pressure. The double vision has resolved, and the Bell's palsy is about 90% improved. I am scheduled for my 2nd vaccine this Sunday, 1/31/ Both Dr want me to go ahead and take it. I have a prescription of Clonidine on hand in case my blood pressure spikes again. It has come back down to about 136/84, which is still high for me. I am absolutely convinced that the blood pressure issue is also from the vaccine. There is no other explanation for my blood pressure doubling.  I hope this letter explains the very unfortunate consequences of my Covid vaccine. I have included the progress notes from dr with this letter. Please feel free to contact me at our office.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I recieved my second dose of the Moderna vaccine on 3/6/21 at 3pm and by 9am on 3/7/21 I had a fever of 101.6 and it would spike up to 102.6 going up and down over the next 2 days. I experienced a high fever that only decreased to a low fever of 100.5 with ibuprofen and cool baths and cold fluids for two days. The injection site was swollen and painful for 3 days just like the first vaccine, but the fever and full body aches accompanied by once of the worst light sensitive headache I have ever experienced lasted for 2 days. The 3rd day was interesting, my fever broke and my lower back now ached very bad and I was weak to stand. The most interesting thing that happened on the third day was a full badly rash that looked and felt like a full body sunburn. My fever had broken, but my skin was bright red and radiated heat of 101.5, but my head temp read normal 98.6 The red sunburn skin cut off dramatically at my wrists. I took pictures because it was so bizarre looking. By Wednesday morning the rash/sunburn was almost 70% gone and I was starting to feel like a normal human being again.  I would like to note that I had a very mild fever 99.9 with my first vaccine shot and my arm was very sore and swollen for 3 days. I did also have a mild fever rash on my belly, back & forearms I would also like to say this was the sickest I have been in over 5+ years ( my second dose) it was no joke! Thank god for my husband taking care of me, I don?t know what I would have done if I was alone.
OTHER_MEDS: None, besides my Kyleena IUD birth control and Ibuprofen

Received first dose of the Pfizer vaccination at 09:35am, about 15 mins later I began to develop petechiae to both my arms and abdomen. I had the nurses look at my petechiae that had developed, then had me sit for another 15 mins. During that time, I began to develop heart palpitations and chest discomfort. They had me sit in another room and evaluated me. My blood pressure was high in the 140's systolic, which is abnormal for me, I?m usually 110 systolic. I began to have some shortness of breath; I wasn't able to take a deep breath. I was taken to the ED to be evaluated for my symptoms. There I was asked a series of questions, they had taken an EKG and my blood pressure was 151 systolic, then was taken to a triage room. MD ran a series of blood work and was given SOLU-Medrol IV push for my allergic reaction and Shortness of breath. I was kept in the ED for about 4 hours. Labs came back normal and was prescribed 20 mg Prednisone by mouth and 25mg Benadryl by mouth to take at home. My diagnose was Allergic reaction, Initial encounter. I was to follow up with my PCP. Followed up with my PCP the following day, 3/12/21 and she had run a CMP and CBC, looked at my petechia and referring me to Oncologist/hematologist to further evaluated for my platelet count and petechiae. She wants to make sure I won't be developing ITP.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient reported to the pharmacy counter after her 1st dose of the COVID19 (Pfizer-Biotech) vaccination within 5 minutes stating "Guys, I don't feel good." One of the pharmacists grabbed her chair and moved it to our check out window and sat down with her to ask her what she was experiencing. I grabbed the blood pressure cuff and returned to the patient. The other pharmacist reported to me that she felt light-headed, dizzy, and that her throat was itchy. We administered 25mg of diphenhydramine (oral tablet) and gave the patient some water. We then checked her BP and it was 68/40, which prompted us to call 911 for assistance. The other pharmacist stayed with her until the paramedics arrived (~15 minutes). About 5 minutes later we rechecked her BP and it jumped to 144/90. I tried to assess the patient's coherence, which began to diminish as she was very confused and could not understand the questions we were asking her. About 1 minute before they arrived, the patient said her throat was feeling worse and swelling, so we went to grab an epinephrine pen. EMT's arrived right as the dose was about to be administered, so we stopped to let them take over.

After a few more minutes of sweating and dry heaving I began feeling better.  The pharmacist got me some paper towels so I could dry myself off as I was drenched in sweat. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I am quoting this from my mother as she is currently unable to type due to the shaking and shivering. "It started with red hot places on both arms, and then it moved to my face. 2 1/2 hours later I began getting really nauseated and began shaking/shivering uncontrollably. I then went to urgent care and on the way there my heart was pounding and racing. After I was admitted they told me that I had tachycardia and my blood pressure was high (I do not usually have high blood pressure). They did an EKG at urgent care and noticed small changes. I was then sent to the ER and was given IV Benadryl and oral steroids. I was put on a heart monitor, and they were able to get my heart rate to go down, but a few hours later it jumped back up. At that point I was referred to a cardiologist and given a prescription for steroids, and then I was discharged. I saw the cardiologist 2 days later, during those two days I still experienced red hot spots on my arm, shortness of breath, Tachycardia, and shivering. When I went to the cardiologist, they did another EKG and said I still have tachycardia and did some bloodwork. The results of the bloodwork were normal and the cardiologist diagnosed it as an unspecified delayed severe allergic reaction. I am still experiencing symptoms and still having to use Benadryl and steroids."
LAB_DATA: EKG noticed tachycardia, and bloodwork was normal.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: There are no adverse effects known at this time.  Patients who came on 2/11/2021 were due back on 3/11/2021. The  system was down and a reminder email could not be sent. We asked the  help desk to for a list of patients from 2/11/2021 to issue a reminder to patients.  An email was sent out to all patients on the list. Patient's wife  received the email. She called our office to ask about the 2nd dose email and a time to come in for the vaccine. Representative from our office registered patient  from the information we received on the spreadsheet from the help desk. She dod not see that the report listed patient as a waitlist patient and was registeredfor his 2nd dose at the clinic for a 2nd dose of Moderna. Patient received a dose of Moderna on 3/11/2021 and upon checking out with the physician onsite it was discovered that he had not received his 1st dose of Moderna at our office on 2/11/2021 but had received his 1st COVID-19 vaccine on 2/23/2021 at a County site and the vaccine he received was Pfizer. Patient received a mixed series within 16 days of each other. He has no known adverse effects at his time. We spoke with the patient and his wife at the close of our clinic explained the error which occurred and let them know we would be filing a report with VAERS. We have made changes to our clinic process and have 3 check points and reviews of vaccination cards in additional to our normal process for 2nd dose patients.
